Introduction

The aim of this report is to present an analysis and exploration of the Wisconsin Breast Cancer Database, which is a dataset that contains a set of variables in a number of patients known to have breast cancer. The final goal of this analysis is to compare the performance of classification models and decision trees to predict if a certain tumor is benign or malignant given the available predictors in the dataset.

This plot allows us to clearly realize that in a benign tumor most of the parameters tend to have a lower value and a much lower range than in a malignant tumor. Therefore, it makes sense to think that if a tumor presents abnormally large values in several parameters at the same time, it probably is a malignant tumor.

Section 1.3: Trying to find the best predictor (or set of predictors)

In this section we face the problem of trying to infer which combination of predictors will produce an optimal outcome and more accurate prediction. In order to solve this, we will write a function that computes the importance of each of the parameters:

  registerDoParallel()
  #performs crossvalidation 10 times through 10 folds
  control <- trainControl(method = "repeatedcv", number = 10, repeats = 10)
  
  feature_imp <- function(model, title, subtitle="") {

  #estimates variable importance
  importance <- varImp(model, scale = TRUE)
  
  #prepare dataframes for plotting
  importance_df_1 <- importance$importance
  importance_df_1$group <- rownames(importance_df_1)
  
  importance_df_2 <- importance_df_1
  importance_df_2$Overall <- 0
  
  importance_df <- rbind(importance_df_1, importance_df_2)
  
  #build the plot
  plot <- ggplot() +
    geom_point(data = importance_df_1, aes(x = Overall, y = group, color = group), size = 2) +
    geom_path(data = importance_df, aes(x = Overall, y = group, color = group, group = group), size = 1) +
    theme(legend.position = "none") +
    labs(
      x = "Importance",
      y = "",
      title = title,
      subtitle = subtitle
    )
  
  #return the plot we just built as a result
  return(plot)
  }

Now we will predict the importance of each of the predictors taking two different approaches: random forest and boosted trees.

Random forest is a supervised learning algorithm that works both for classification and regression tasks. It works by building a set of trees which in turn merges so as to get a more precise prediction.

Boosting is a technique that can also be applied to classification and regression problems, and is particularly useful in the context of decision trees.

In sectinon 4 we will introduce bagged trees. Bagging is a procedure that involves creating multiple copies of the original training data set using the bootstrap, fitting a separate decision tree to each copy, and then combining all of the trees in order to create a single predictive model.

Boosting works in a similar way, but each tree now is grown using information from previously grown trees.

Having provided an explanation for those concepts, we now proceed to use the function in combination with these techniques:

  #we turn Class into a factor variable so as to run the importance function
  breastCancer$Class = as.factor(breastCancer$Class)
  
  #we change nuclei to a numeric variable
  breastCancer$bare_nuclei = as.numeric(breastCancer$bare_nuclei)
  
  set.seed(27)
  
  #we now use random forest (mehtod = "rf") to train the data
  imp_md <- train(Class ~ ., data = breastCancer, method = "rf", preProcess = c("scale", "center"), trControl = control)

  #and we plot it
  p1 <- feature_imp(imp_md, title = "Breast cancer dataset", subtitle = "Determined with Random Forest and repeated cross validation (10 repeats, 10 times) ")
  grid.arrange(p1, ncol = 3, widths = c(0.3, 0.35, 0.35))

It can be seen that the random forest method returns size_uniformity, shape_uniformity and bare_nuclei as the three strongest predictors. Let’s compare this outcome to the one we will get when we use the function and the boosting trees approach:

Section 2. Decision Trees I: Boosted Trees

In this section (and the upcoming ones), we will classify the tumors into benign or malignant using a range of statistical learning techniques and compute the misclassification rate for each of them. Our ultimate goal is to decide on an optimal classification model weighting the advantages and drawbacks of each of the methods.

Section 2.1: Creation of the Model

  library("gbm")
  set.seed(100)
  
  #turn the values in the factor variable Class (2 and 4) to 0 and 1 to represent benign and malignant tumors respectively
  breastCancer$Class_binary <- ifelse(breastCancer$Class == 2,0,
                            ifelse(breastCancer$Class == 4, 1, NA))
  
  #split the data into training and testing data
  train <- sample(1:nrow(breastCancer),400)
  breastCancer_test <- breastCancer[-train,]
  
  #create the boosted decision trees model 
  boost.breastCancer <- gbm (Class_binary~.-Class,data=breastCancer[train,],distribution = "bernoulli",n.trees =  300, interaction.depth   = 2)
  
  #use the model to generate a prediction
  yhat.boost <- predict(boost.breastCancer,newdata=breastCancer[-train,],n.trees = 300,type="response")
  
  #show the predicted values on a table
  table(true=breastCancer_test$Class_binary,prediction=ifelse(yhat.boost<0.5,0,1))
##     prediction
## true   0   1
##    0 199   2
##    1  39  59

Section 2.2: Performace Review of the Boosted Trees Model

To measure the performace of the model we will use a metric called misclassification rate, which we define as:

\[MR = \frac{misclassified\hspace{0.2cm}cases}{total\hspace{0.2cm}number\hspace{0.2cm} of\hspace{0.2cm} classified\hspace{0.2cm}cases} \] This definition makes us aware of the fact that the lower it is, the better because we want a prediction as accurate as possible. In this model we got 41/299 predictions wrong, which amounts to 13.71%.

Boosted Trees Misclassification Rate

13.71 %

Section 3. Decision Trees II: Pruned Trees

Pruned trees involve growing a large tree and outputting a subset of that tree as our final solution, thus pruning it. The particular pruning technique we will here is cost complexity pruning, which involves having a tuning parameter α to balance the subtrees’ complexity and its fit to the data.

The procedure then consists of selecting the best possible value for the tuning parameter by means of cross-validation and then getting the corresponding subtree in the original dataset associated with that value of α.

Section 3.1: Creation of the Model

Section 5. Alternatives to tree-based methods in classification problems I: Logistic Regression

In this section, we will build a logistic regression model and perform cross-validation on it using Akaike’s Information Criterion, which a way of penalizing a model for having too many variables. Thus, the lower the AIC value, the better.

It is possible to obtain the AIC by means of this equation, where n represents the number of cases in the model, SSE the sum of squared errors for the model and k the number of predictor variables.

\[AIC=n(ln)\frac{SSE}{n}+2k\]

Section 5.1: Creation of the Logistic Regression Model

set.seed(100)

breastCancer.raw<-read.csv("breast-cancer-wisconsin.data.csv")

#rename the variables.
breastCancer<-dplyr::rename(breastCancer.raw, ID=id.number,
          thickness=Clump.Thickness,
          size_uniformity=Uniformity.of.Cell.Size, 
          shape_uniformity=Uniformity.of.Cell.Shape,
          adhesion=Marginal.Adhesion,
          size_epithelial=Single.Epithelial.Cell.Size,
          bare_nuclei=Bare.Nuclei,
          bland_chromatin=Bland.Chromatin,
          normal_nucleoli=Normal.Nucleoli,
          mitoses=Mitoses)

rownames(breastCancer)<-c(1:nrow(breastCancer))

#Legend labelling
breastCancer$Class <- ifelse(breastCancer$Class == "2",0,
                          ifelse(breastCancer$Class == "4", 1, NA))

#Splitting dataset into approximately 50:50
train<-sample(1:nrow(breastCancer),400)

#Creating and storing test and training datasets
data.training<-breastCancer[train,]
data.test<-breastCancer[-train,]


#cross-validation on logistic model using AIC.
loocv_default<-function(dataset){
  n<-nrow(dataset)
  loocv_prediction<-rep(0,n)
  
  for (i in 1:n){
    dataset.loocv<-dataset[-i,]
    glm.model<-glm(Class~bare_nuclei + thickness + bland_chromatin + shape_uniformity + adhesion + mitoses,data=data.training,binomial)
    predict_for_row<-predict(glm.model,newdata=dataset[i,],type="response")
    
    if (predict_for_row<0.5){loocv_prediction[i]<-0}else{loocv_prediction[i]<-1}
  }
  misclassified<-length(which(loocv_prediction!=dataset$Class))
  rate<-misclassified/n
  return(rate)
}

loocv_default(data.training)
## [1] 0.0175

Section 6. Alternatives to tree-based methods in classification problems II: K Nearest Neighbours

K Nearest Neighbours is another supervised learning technique that allows us to classify the data into factors based on a given training dataset, returning a solution based on the association of new cases with the K most similar cases in the training data.

Section 6.1: Creation of the KNN Model

#run knn on training data
set.seed(100)

breastCancer.raw<-read.csv("breast-cancer-wisconsin.data.csv")

#rename the variables.

          adhesion=Marginal.Adhesion,

Section 6.2: Performance Review of the KNN

In this section the performance of the KNN classification model will be assesed by means of computing the misclassification rate. When it comes to the trainig data, the model got 13/400 predictions wrong, which amounts to 3.25%.

In the test data, it got 16/299 predictions wrong, which amounts to 5.3%. Obviusly, we expected the model to be less accurate with the test data, which explains the presence of a higher misclassification rate.

KNN Misclassification Rate:

5.3 %

Conclusion and Final Thoughts

This report presents an analysis of the Wisconsin Breast Cancer Dataset and an example of how to build both tree-based and non-tree-based statistical learning classification models to predict the diagnosis of breast cancer tumour class (benign or malignant) through the analysis of cytological characteristics of breast cancer cells.

Regarding tree-based methods, a number of differerent techniques have been carried out: pruned tree, bagged tree, boosted tree and random forest models have been built, and we can regard the random forest approach as the most effective amongst this group because it presents the lowest misclassification rate, 2.75%.

However, when it comes to the two non-tree based approaches built in the latter sections of this report, k-nearest-neighbors and logistic regression, we must acknowledge logistic regression as the best method overvall because it presents a misclassification rate of 1.75%.

As this analysis shows, machine learning has the potential to become a key tool in the advance of modern computational biology, as it holds the capacity to, given enough quality data, make accurate predictions that may help improve medical treatment and, hopefully, advance some diagnoses.
